{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "It requires smaller number of gates while maintaining a path from every input qubit to every output qubit.",
    "It is also less expressive with a restrained set of possible orthogonal matrices and fewer trainable parameters.The butterfly circuit requires logarithmic circuit depth, a linear number of gates, and exhibits a higher level of expressivity.",
    "It originates from the classical Cooley-Tukey algorithm [27] used for Fast Fourier Transform and, it performs an operation analogous to the method presented in [28] for classical recurrent neural networks when it is implemented with RBS gates.",
    "Note that the butterfly circuit requires the ability to apply gates on all possible qubit pairs.",
    "As shown in [24], quantum orthogonal layers can be generalised to work with inputs which encode a vector on a larger basis."
  ],
